description: The screenshot shows a Windows XP desktop with the mouse cursor hovering over the desktop background. This indicates the user's next action will be performed on the desktop itself, such as right-clicking to access a context menu for personalization options or other system settings.

The screenshot displays a Windows XP desktop with an autumn-themed background depicting a path through trees with orange leaves. A context menu is open, having been activated by a right-click. The menu options visible are: "Arrange Icons By", "Refresh", "Paste", "Paste Shortcut", "New", and "Properties". The mouse cursor is hovering over the "Properties" option.

Additionally, a submenu titled "Arrange Icons By" is expanded, presenting choices like "Name", "Size", "Type", and "Modified".

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Appearance" tab. 

At the top, a tabbed menu allows navigation between different setting categories: "Themes," "Desktop," "Screen Saver," and "Appearance" (currently selected), and "Settings."

The "Appearance" tab focuses on visual customization. The main area displays a preview of the "Active Window" appearance, including "Window Text" style. Users can modify these elements using the controls to the right of the preview. 

At the bottom of the window, standard dialog buttons are present: "OK" (to apply changes and close the window), "Cancel" (to discard changes and close the window), and "Apply" (to apply changes without closing the window).
The screenshot shows the Windows XP desktop with the "Display Properties" window open. The "Themes" tab is now active, instead of the "Appearance" tab.
The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab instead of the "Appearance" tab. The "Screen Saver" tab is highlighted, indicating it is currently selected.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Appearance" tab. The "Appearance" tab is still selected.  The most notable difference is the "Theme:" dropdown menu now displays "Windows XP (Modified)" instead of "Windows XP".

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP. The "Screen Saver" tab is now active, instead of the "Appearance" tab.  The rest of the elements within the window remain unchanged.
The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Themes" tab instead of the "Appearance" tab. The "Screen Saver" tab is not selected.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Themes" tab, within the Windows XP operating system. 

At the top, a series of tabs - "Themes," "Desktop," "Screen Saver," "Appearance," and "Settings" - allow navigation through different customization options. 

The "Themes" tab, currently active, allows the user to select a visual theme for their desktop. A dropdown menu labeled "Theme:" displays the currently selected theme as "Windows XP (Modified)".  Below, a preview window titled "Active Window" showcases the selected theme's appearance using a sample window with the text "Window Text".

Three buttons are located to the right of the "Theme:" dropdown menu:
 - "Save As...": This button enables the user to save the currently applied theme with a new name. 
 - "Delete": This button allows the user to delete a custom theme. It appears inactive, suggesting the current theme is a system default and cannot be deleted.
 - "Apply": Located at the bottom right of the window, this button confirms and applies any changes made within the "Display Properties" window. 

At the bottom right corner of the screen, the system tray displays the time as 11:11 AM.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. The "Screen Saver" tab is now active, with the "Themes" tab no longer active. 

The preview window now displays a blank screen with the "Windows XP" logo in the center, indicating the screen saver is set to "None". 

The "Save As..." and "Delete" buttons, previously present in the "Themes" tab, are no longer visible. 

The "Theme:" dropdown menu is replaced with a dropdown menu labeled "Screen saver:". This menu shows "Windows XP" as the selected option. 

A new button labeled "Settings" appears to the right of the "Screen saver:" dropdown. 

A new text field labeled "Wait:" appears below the "Screen saver:" dropdown menu.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab is now active instead of the "Themes" tab. The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu shows "Windows XP" is selected. The "Wait" time is set to "10 minutes" and the "On resume, password protect" checkbox is unchecked.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab, in the Windows XP operating system. 

The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu currently displays "Windows XP," indicating the active screensaver. A numeric field labeled "Wait:" is set to "10 minutes," determining the idle time before the screensaver activates.  The checkbox labeled "On resume, password protect" is currently unchecked. 

Below the preview monitor, four buttons are visible:
- **Settings:** Currently inactive (greyed out) due to the "None" screensaver selection. In a scenario with an adjustable screensaver selected, this button would become active, allowing for customization.
- **Preview:**  Inactive (greyed out) due to the "None" screensaver selection. In a scenario with an active screensaver selected, this button would provide a preview of the chosen screensaver.
- **OK:**  Clicking this button closes the "Display Properties" window and saves any changes made within this window.
- **Cancel:**  Clicking this button closes the "Display Properties" window and discards any changes made within this window.
- **Apply:**  Clicking this button immediately applies any changes made within this window without closing it. 

Below the buttons, a text instruction guides the user: "To adjust monitor power settings and save energy, click Power."  A button labeled "Power..." provides access to further power management options.

The screenshot displays the "Display Properties" window with the "Screen Saver" dropdown menu expanded, revealing a list of available screensavers. The "Screen Saver" tab is currently active. 

Content Changes:
- The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu is now expanded and the "None" option is highlighted. 
- The "Settings" and "Preview" buttons are now inactive (greyed out).

The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu is open, displaying a list of available screensavers. The option "None" is currently selected, indicated by the blue highlight. This selection disables the screensaver function. 

Below the preview window, several buttons provide further actions:
- **Settings:** This button, currently inactive (greyed out), would allow adjustments to the selected screensaver's settings.
- **Preview:** This button allows the user to preview the currently selected screensaver (in this case, no screensaver).
- **Power...:** This button opens the "Power Options Properties" window, enabling the user to configure power management settings. 
- **Cancel:** This button discards any changes made within this window and closes the "Display Properties" window.
- **Apply:** This button applies the selected screensaver ("None") to the system settings.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

At the top, we see four tabs: "Themes," "Desktop," the currently active "Screen Saver" tab, and "Appearance," and "Settings." This indicates the user is currently able to adjust settings related to the screen saver.

Under "Screen Saver," a dropdown menu displays "(None)" as the selected option, indicating no screensaver is currently active. Below, a numerical field labeled "Wait:" is visible, although the exact value is cut off in the screenshot. This field likely controls the duration of inactivity before the screensaver activates.  A checkbox labeled "On resume, password protect" is located to the right, allowing users to enable password protection upon returning from the screensaver.

Further down, three buttons are visible: "Settings," "Preview," and "Power." The "Settings" button likely allows customization of the chosen screensaver. "Preview" presumably offers a simulation of the selected screensaver. Lastly, the "Power" button, when clicked, likely leads to more advanced power management options.

At the bottom of the window, standard buttons: "OK," "Cancel," and "Apply" are present. The "OK" button would apply any changes made and close the window. "Cancel" discards any alterations and closes the window. "Apply" would enact the changes without closing the window.
